2 Clean data

insurance <- 
  insurance %>% 
  mutate(
    across(where(is.character), factor)
  )
insurance

3 EDA

insurance %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Claims)) + 
  geom_bar()

insurance %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Policies, Claims)) + 
  geom_point()

insurance %>% 
  select(where(is.factor), Claims) %>% 
  pivot_longer(-Claims) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(value, Claims)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  facet_wrap(~name, scales = "free")

insurance %>% 
  mutate(
    p = Claims / Policies
  ) %>% 
  select(p, where(is.factor)) %>% 
  pivot_longer(-p) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(value, p)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  facet_wrap(~name, scales = "free")

6 Residual checking

insurance <- 
  insurance %>% 
  add_column(
    M1_res = residuals(M1, type = "pearson"), 
    M1_fit = fitted(M1)
  )
p <- insurance %>% 
  select(where(is.double)) %>% 
  pivot_longer(-M1_res) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(value, M1_res)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(~name, scale = "free")
p

p + scale_x_log10()
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous x-axis

insurance %>% 
  select(where(is.factor), M1_res) %>% 
  pivot_longer(-M1_res) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(value, M1_res)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  facet_wrap(~name, scale = "free")

The log additive (multiplicative) model

\[ \mu_{ijk}=n_{ijk}e^{\alpha_i+\beta_j+\gamma_k} \]

provides an adequate description of the data, where

  • \(\alpha_i\) is the effect of District \(i\),

  • \(\beta_j\) is the effect of Engine \(j\),

  • \(\gamma_k\) is the effect of Age group \(k\) and

  • \(n_{ijk}\) is the number of policies.

  • Based on the parameter estimates District 4 (major cities) carries significantly higher risk than the other three categories that appear to be roughly equal. Since \(e^{0.23421}=1.26\) we estimate that claims occur roughly 26% more frequently in major cities.

  • Based on the parameter estimates, the frequency of claims also increases with engine size and decreases with age.
